@node intro "Introduction"

    This program is a small CLI based utility that generates a top download
chart for the FLE filebase.

    The chart that is generated is display over the ANSI background by
resetting the cursor to the top left of the display, and using ANSI position
codes to position the text.

	This keeps the filesize to a minimum, and also enables you to edit the
FLETopDl.ANSI into an animation, if you so wish, using the output from the
program as the last frame.

    Click @{"here" link main} to return to the main index.
@endnode

@node sysreq "System Requirements"

    FLETopDL doesn't use any version 3 specific routines, and so should be ok
on any version of the OS that can run a Blitz Basic 2.1 program.

    As far as memory requirements, FLETopDL runs in LESS than 100K, so there
shouldn't be any real problems, except in the most desperate circumstances.

    Click @{"here" link main} to return to the main index.
@endnode

@node inst "Installation & Use"

   FLETopDL simply needs to be put somewhere in your search path, however,
the file FLETopDL.ANSI must be in the same directory as the executable file
'FLeTopDL'.

   The program will look for Files:datafiles/Filelist.data, in order to
access the filebase, and will output the top Downloads list wherever you want.

   The program should be called from the CLI with one command line option, the
name of the output file.

   	e.g.
		typing 'FLETopDL t:chart' and hitting return, would list the top 10
downloads into 't:chart'.

   If you leave out the CLI parameter, then the parameter list will be
displayed.

   When editing FLETopDL.ANSI, do not put any text or graphics in the area
makred with XXX's.  This area is where the download chart will appear when
the programs output is shown.

    Click @{"here" link main} to return to the main index.
@endnode

